@NODE iniInsta ini.guide/Installing

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}Installation instructions@{ub}    @{" Usage >> " Link iniUsage}

@{b}(User install)@{ub}

Simply copy the file libs/ini.library to your LIBS:  directory!  For
applications  that  supports it, you can now edit it's settings using
your favourite text editor!

@{b}(Installing upgrades)@{ub}

To install an upgraded version of ini.library, overwrite the
existing library with the new one, and either type "flushlibs"
in Shell or reboot your Amiga.

@{b}(Developer install)@{ub}

From                             To

libs/ini.library                 LIBS:
docs/ini_lib.doc                 Your Autodocs directory
fd/ini_lib.fd                    Your "fd" directory
include/clib/ini_protos.h        INCLUDE:clib/
include/libraries/ini_lib.h      INCLUDE:libraries/
include/libraries/ini_lib.i      INCLUDE:libraries/
include/pragmas/ini_pragmas.h    INCLUDE:pragmas/
include/proto/ini.h              INCLUDE:proto/

The remaining files              Wherever you want!


Now   you're   ready   to  either  run  applications  that  utilizes
ini.library,  or starting to incorporate ini's power into your C / C++
or Asm sourcecode!


@{" << Home  " Link Main}  Back to the table of contents.

@ENDNODE


@NODE iniUsage ini.guide/Usage

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}Usage of ini files and ini.library@{ub}    @{" History >> " Link iniHisto}


@{b}An "ini" file (Initialization file) is built up as follows:@{ub}

[Context]

Item1 = Value1
Item2 = Value1, Value2, Value3, Value4, Value5
Item3 = Float1

[Context2]

Item1 = Float1
...


Here's the basic operation on ini files:

@{b}1. open a default ini file.@{ub}

(you may even specify a buffer to use as a default file that
 will be created and processed)

@{b}2. get context.@{ub}

@{b}3. get values of items related to this context.@{ub}

(store the values in your own variables)

@{b}4. close ini file.@{ub}


To  create  or  modify  an  ini file, you're able to add, remove and
modify  contexts  and  items  to  your liking.  Even "TRUE/FALSE" or
"YES/NO"  values  are  implemented, making your setting file easy to
read for users!

Have a look at the file Examples/src/C/INI_Example.C to see the C sourcecode
of how to use ini.library.


@{" << Home  " Link Main}  Back to the table of contents.

@ENDNODE

@NODE iniHisto ini.guide/History

@{" << Home  " Link Main}    @{b}History of ini.library@{ub}    @{" Authors >> " Link iniAutho}

@{i}Most recent version always on the top of the list.@{ui}

@{b}v33.00 (09 Aug 2001)@{ub}
		* Fatal crashing bug with iniPutStr() fixed. If you use iniWriteStr()
		  or iniPutStr(), please open ini.library with v33 or you risk a crash!
        * Case sensitive search didn't work for context items. Fixed!
        * AutoDocs fixed.
        * Example added which demonstrates writing to an INI file.


@{b}v32.01 (08 Aug 2000)@{ub}
		* Autodocs are finally up to date.
		* Added Amigaguide version of Autodocs.

@{b}v32.00 (22 Jul 2000)@{ub}
		* Bug fix: ini.library would crash using empty contexts or empty files.
		* Bug fix: iniGetStr() did not allocate string.
		* Bug fix: iniCreateContext() did not set brackets and linefeed in the line buffer.
		* Bug fix: iniPutxxxA() did not check for valid context item.
		* iniPutxxxA() now expands data array if required.
		* iniReadxxx() now accepts NULL pointer as context name. In this case the functions
		scan through all contexts.
		* iniWritexxx() now creates a context or context item if nonexistant.

@{b}v31.00 Release 2 (06 Sep 1999)@{ub}
		* Done some fixes to includes. Added inline/ include.
		* Fixed bugs in example sources.
		* Added Utils/Bin2Hex directory and executable.

(Note to BB2/GFA/E developers - please rebuild your library files to
reflect the changes!)

@{b}v31.00 (13 Aug 1999)@{ub}
        * First public release.


